@zRains thanks for the review. I will be addressing these issues shortly. While I understand the issues with Jquery upgrade, this feature in no way impacts the existing functionality and does not impact the current written code. Intention is to develop the modernized version of the application (mostly written in React) while keeping the current version intact. As and when stable, we will be able to remove the previously written versions of the modules and make the modernized one as the default version. 
Having a separate branch for the same would mean development in isolation which is not the case. To leverage the contributions, we can consider having the changes in trunk branch where the community can see the functionality to switch and contribute according to their capacity.
Let me know your thoughts.

